Modelling cellular mechanical properties in the crypt

Axel Almet

2 October 2018

Generalised-set up

We model the crypt as a planar, growing, inextensible elastic rod attached to an underlying foundation, whose attachments remodel over time to the current rod shape. Tissue growth is encapsulated by the growth stretch \(\gamma\), modelling a local increase of the initial arc length \(S_0\); that is, \[\begin{align} \gamma = \frac{\partial s}{\partial S_0}. \end{align}\] The equations describing geometric constraints and balance of linear and angular momentum are given by: \[\begin{align} &x' = \gamma\cos\theta,\\ &y' = \gamma\sin\theta,\\ &n_x' = k\gamma(x - p_x),\qquad\mbox{where}\qquad \dot{p}_x = \rho(x - p_x),\\ &n_y' = k\gamma(y - p_y),\qquad\mbox{where}\qquad \dot{p}_y = \rho(y - p_y),\\ &\theta' = E_b\gamma m,\\ &m' = \gamma(n_x\sin\theta - n_y\cos\theta). \end{align}\] For simplicity, we assume the rod is clamped horizontally at the boundaries: \[\begin{align} x(0) = 0, \qquad x(1) = 0, \qquad y(0) = y(1) = y_0, \qquad \theta(0) = \theta(1) = 0. \end{align}\]

Specifying \(E_b\)

\[\begin{align} E_b(S_0) = 1 - \frac{1}{2}e^{-\left(\frac{S_0 - 0.5}{\sigma_E}\right)^2}. \end{align}\] \[\begin{align} E_b(s) = 1 - \frac{1}{2}e^{-\left(\frac{s - 0.5l}{\sigma_E}\right)^2}. \end{align}\]
